{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:37:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:37:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22663"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22663"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0,0.05,0.15,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15610"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114376"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15610"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22663"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96377"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"976"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3836"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11620"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"12974"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47039"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114376"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man is seen on a General Practitioner home visit with increasing difficulty managing his pain. He is under palliative care with stage IV lung cancer with widespread metastases to his spine, pelvis, liver and brain. He was diagnosed eight months ago in which he declined any chemo-radiotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is unable to sit upright in bed due to pain in his pelvis, in which he finds difficulty in eating and drinking. He has avoided solid foods since his pelvic pain as he fears choking on his food. He has lost 2kg in the past few days from the lack of oral intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is currently on regular 10mg slow-release morphine twice daily with rapid release morphine PRN (total morphine use in the past 24 hours 42.5mg). He also takes paracetamol and ondansetron PRN.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is lying supine on his bed and appears cachectic and in pain. All vital signs are within normal limits except a heart rate of 110/min. The patient has sunken eyes, loss of skin turgor and dry mucous membranes. There are no abnormalities on cardiopulmonary examination. There is tenderness on palpation of the lower back and pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Switch to a transdermal fentanyl patch","Prescribe a benzodiazepine","Switch oral morphine to morphine sachet (in suspension)","Increase oral slow-release morphine to 15mg twice daily","Use continuous subcutaneous infusion of morphine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching the patient to a continuous subcutaneous infusion of morphine \u003C/strong\u003Eis a safe temporary alternative to work out the patient\u0027s analgesia requirement / best analgesia method before switching to other options e.g. transdermal patches\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E The patient could be an admitted to hospital given his poor control of pain symptoms, or this could be set up at home on liaising with the palliative care team. An interim continuous subcutaneous infusion pump can be given to work out analgesia requirements first before switching to other options more manageable in an outpatient setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to a transdermal fentanyl patch \u003C/strong\u003Emay be a useful non-oral alternative. Fentanyl is a synthetic opioid that can be used in the treatment of chronic pain and the transdermal patch provides a slow steady release of analgesia into the blood. Fentanyl patches take 24\u201372\u00a0hours to reach maximum effect and steady-state concentration may not be reached until the second patch is applied. By switching oral morphine to a fentanyl patch immediately, the interim pain between the switch may not be covered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing a benzodiazepine\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in end-of-life care to manage behavioural symptoms such as anxiousness and restlessness. However, benzodiazepines does not provide pain relief and may increase the risk of severe respiratory depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching oral morphine to morphine suspension\u003C/strong\u003E might help with administration, but it doesn\u0027t address the underlying issue of the patient\u0027s difficulty with oral intake due to pain when sitting upright. A parenteral route of administration would be more appropriate in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease oral slow-realease morphine to 15mg twice daily \u003C/strong\u003Emay help with analgesia but does not consider the difficult with oral intake and need for change of administration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A continuous PCA infusion is a safe temporary alternative to evaluate a patient\u0027s 24-hour analgesia requirement before switching to another pain regimen."],"references":["Tassinari D, Sartori S, Tamburini E, et al. Transdermal fentanyl as a front-line approach to moderate-severe pain: a meta-analysis of randomized clinical trials. J Palliat Care 2009; 25:172.","Hadley G, Derry S, Moore RA, Wiffen PJ. Transdermal fentanyl for cancer pain. Cochrane Database Syst Rev 2013; :CD010270."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96377"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22663"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96377"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-16T07:55:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-16T07:55:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15610"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114376"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"create